COARDS, CF-1.6, ACDD-1.3, NCCSV-1.0: Radon:\nThe PMEL radon instrument is a \dual flow loop
column4: two filtered radon detector\". The general features of the instrument are described in Whittlestone and Zahorowski
column5: Baseline radon detectors for shipboard use: Development and deployment in the First Aerosol Characterization Experiment (ACE1)
column11: 1998. The instrument response is due to radon gas
column12: not radon daughters (all of the existing radon daughters are filtered out before entering the decay/counting tank). The instrument registers the total number of decay counts per 30 minute interval on a filter (wire screen) arising from the decay of radon in the tank. The volume of the decay/counting tank was 905 l and the sample flow rate into and out of the tank was typically 70 l/min. The response time of the radon instrument is limited to about 30 minutes by the radiological decay time constants of the radon daughters on the wire screen filter. Thus
column13: the start time given in the data file is 15 minutes prior to the midpoint of the counting interval. The instrument was calibrated with a known radon source in Seattle before the cruise and a second calibration was performed after the instrument was shipped back to PMEL. Radon concentrations are given in mBq m-3."
